noble /ˈnəʊbəl/

(nobler,noblest) 

1. ADJ If you say that someone is a noble person, you admire and respect them because they are unselfish and morally good. 高尚的 [表赞许] 

例： He was an upright and noble man who was always willing to help in any way he could. 他是一个正直、高尚的人，总是愿意尽其所能来帮忙。 

2. nobly ADV 高尚地 [ADV with v] 

例： Eric's sister had nobly volunteered to help with the gardening. 埃里克的姐姐无私地主动帮忙做些园艺工作。 

3. ADJ If you say that something is a noble idea, goal, or action, you admire it because it is based on high moral principles. 崇高的 [表赞许] 

例： He had implicit faith in their noble intentions. 他对他们的崇高目标深信不疑。 

例： We'll always justify our actions with noble sounding theories. 我们将始终用崇高的理论思想指导我们的行动。 

4. ADJ If you describe something as noble , you think that its appearance or quality is very impressive, making it superior to other things of its type. 卓越的; 超群的 

例： ...the great parks with their noble trees. …树木参天的大公园。 

5. ADJ Noble means belonging to a high social class and having a title. 高贵的; 贵族的 

例： ...rich and noble families. …富有而高贵的家族。

